---
import DocsLayout from '@/layouts/docs.astro'
---

<DocsLayout page="/">
  <h1>Introduction</h1>
  <p>
    <code>func</code> is a small decorator-based CLI framework for TypeScript. Define commands
    as classes, register them in a <code>FuncModule</code>, and let <code>func</code> resolve
    command names, paths, flags, values, validation, and error handling.
  </p>
  <p>
    The current core is organized around explicit modules, method handlers, field
    options, typed context injection, and optional services. <code>funcgo</code>
    stays focused on project setup, local TypeScript execution, and production bundling.
  </p>
  <p>
    You can create a project in seconds with the <a href="/guide"
      >Quick-start Guide</a
    >.
  </p>

  <h2>Features</h2>
  <ul>
    <li>
      Tiny production bundles by default. See a reference output <a
        href="https://github.com/unix/func/blob/master/examples/gzbundle/archived.tar.gz"
        >here</a
      >
    </li>
    <li>
      Application modules with imported feature modules and registered services
    </li>
    <li>
      Named commands, major commands, missing-command handlers, and path handlers
    </li>
    <li>Field options for flags, scalar values, and repeated string values</li>
    <li>
      Validation decorators for required values, enums, dependencies, exclusions, and
      custom checks
    </li>
    <li>Typed context injection for parsed input, registry data, and exceptions</li>
    <li>
      Local and global error handling through <code>@Catch</code> and
      <code>@CatchAll</code>
    </li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Where It Fits</h2>
  <p>
    <code>func</code> is a good fit when you want a small TypeScript command line tool
    with clear command boundaries, automatic option parsing, reusable services, and simple
    packaging. It is intentionally compact rather than a full terminal UI, prompt toolkit,
    or general task runner.
  </p>
  <p>
    Start with <a href="/guide">Guide</a> to create a project, then read
    <a href="/concepts">Core Concepts</a> for command structure. Field values, parameter
    injection, and error handling each have their own focused page.
  </p>
</DocsLayout>
